The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" (renamed "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the United States), at literary festivals and bookstores everywhere. They had ample reason to do so.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a symbol of resilience and perseverance.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
Eight movies based on this book have grossed a cumulative total of $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
For people of a certain age with a literary mindset, it's hard to imagine a day when the global audience wasn't captivated by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I'm always amazed when I think back to my students' poor reaction to the book "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included it in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestselling American Books" course since 1993.
This course examines popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to reflect on why and how these best-selling works have captured their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final book that represents a popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the potato blight fiercely attacked the American coast.
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently released the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," into bookstores.
The organization also published the third book in the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
By the end of the month, Rowling's novels had claimed the top three spots on the New York Times Best Seller list, and the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone had topped the bestseller list for paperback books.
Time magazine even put the bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is everywhere in sight.
My students are eager to know why such enthusiasm exists.
Goodness, they were utterly disappointed.
To them, the Harry Potter series is nothing more than second-rate nonsense, barely worth mentioning when compared to cherished series like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings from their childhood memories.
Although their childhoods had barely passed a few years ago, they criticized "Harry Potter" just like many notorious adult critics, calling it "contrived," "poorly written," "cliche," and "boring."
Please provide the sentence you would like me to translate.
In their eyes, Harry had neither miracles, nor wit, nor warmth.
The students' resentment surprised me, but in retrospect, there was nothing to be overly concerned about.
Although adults have always formed a significant part of the Harry Potter audience, these students are precisely in an incorrect age group that prevents them from objectively understanding the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were already past the age of accepting new children's books, yet still too young to have their own children (at that time, I had just had my own child). They insisted impatiently that although the Harry Potter series was now immensely popular, it would soon be forgotten by people.
In the autumn of the following year, that is, in 2000, the next batch of students also chose *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone* as their final analysis text, just like their predecessors, confidently rejecting the book.
Let's fast forward to spring of 2007.
After putting the course on hold for several years, I taught "Popular American Books" again.
When students chose the final analysis book, they chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
While I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not university students when they first read Rowling's works, but rather teenagers in their teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This means they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione into young adulthood.
The same thing happened again in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not just a label.
Would Harry disappear from memory?
It's impossible as long as we are still alive.
Since 2010, I have taught the popular book course twice, and in both instances, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final presentations.
Are you tired of Porter?
Based on the feedback I received from students in my other course, "Children's Literature," where I teach Rowling's works, this is unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not select "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone," instead I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban"—this is my favorite among the seven Harry Potter novels. It marks the transition of the series from children's literature to young adult fiction, and it offers a complex portrayal of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also love this book the most.
But how long can the Harry Potter series maintain its popularity?
Every time I teach children's literature, I begin with a poll: "Which of the books on the list did you read as a child?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the following years, the percentage continued to decline—reaching 87% in 2014 and dropping to 81% in 2016.
None of these are science, I know.
But I'm curious: when I teach "Children's Literature" again next spring, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is constantly declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Is there still a balance point ahead where the percentage can remain stable and stop decreasing?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I was happy to have invited him into my classroom.
